Pico 0 component diagnostic firmware.

Use this project when debugging one component at a time before wiring it into an
active puzzle Pico. Upload it to a Raspberry Pi Pico W, wire exactly one device,
then choose the test from the Raspberry Pi using MQTT.

MQTT command topics:

```text
escape/debug/pico0/set_test
escape/debug/pico0/start
escape/debug/pico0/stop
escape/debug/pico0/status
```

MQTT debug output topics:

```text
escape/debug/pico0/online
escape/debug/pico0/current_test
escape/debug/pico0/event
escape/debug/pico0/telemetry
escape/debug/pico0/error
```

Available tests:

```text
idle
ws2812
pir
magnetic_switch
copper_contact
button
potentiometer
relay_lock
smart_film_relay
```

Example commands from the Raspberry Pi:

```bash
mosquitto_sub -h localhost -v -t 'escape/debug/pico0/#'
mosquitto_pub -h localhost -t escape/debug/pico0/set_test -m ws2812
mosquitto_pub -h localhost -t escape/debug/pico0/set_test -m pir
mosquitto_pub -h localhost -t escape/debug/pico0/stop -m stop
mosquitto_pub -h localhost -t escape/debug/pico0/status -m status
```

WS2812B LED strip test:

```text
5V USB pigtail + -> LED strip 5V+
5V USB pigtail - -> LED strip GND
Pico GND         -> LED strip GND
Pico GPIO 17     -> 330-470 ohm resistor -> LED strip DIN
```

Use the strip input side marked DIN or the side the arrows point away from. The
test lights LEDs 0 through 20 one at a time every 200ms, cycles through a rainbow
gradient, waits 1500ms, clears the strip, and repeats.

If the test publishes telemetry but the strip stays dark, check these in order:

1. LED strip GND and Pico GND are directly connected.
2. USB pigtail 5V+ and GND are actually powered.
3. GPIO 17 is wired to DIN, not DOUT.
4. The strip is WS2812B/NeoPixel-compatible.
5. Try a 3.3V-to-5V data level shifter such as 74AHCT125.
6. Try a short strip segment in case the first pixel is damaged.

PIR motion test:

```text
PIR VCC -> 5V supply, or Pico 3V3 if your PIR supports 3.3V
PIR GND -> Pico GND and supply GND
PIR OUT -> Pico GPIO 6
```

Many PIR sensors need 30-60 seconds of warm-up after power is applied. They
detect body heat moving across zones, so a hand directly over the dome may not
always trigger as clearly as stepping sideways in front of it. If PIR OUT is 5V,
use a level shifter or resistor divider before Pico GPIO 6.

Magnetic switch test:

```text
Pico GPIO 15 -> one side of reed/magnetic switch
Pico GND     -> other side of reed/magnetic switch
```

The firmware uses INPUT_PULLUP for this test. The idle state should read 1, and
the triggered/closed state should read 0.

Copper contact test:

```text
Pico GPIO 15 -> one copper contact
Pico GND     -> other copper contact
```

The firmware uses INPUT_PULLUP. When the copper path closes, the state should
change from 1 to 0 and the trigger counter should increase.

Button test:

```text
Pico GPIO 15 -> one side of button
Pico GND     -> other side of button
```

The firmware uses INPUT_PULLUP. Pressed should read 0.

Potentiometer test:

```text
Pico 3V3 OUT -> one outer potentiometer leg
Pico GND     -> other outer potentiometer leg
Pico GPIO 26 / ADC0 -> center wiper leg
```

Telemetry reports raw 12-bit ADC values from 0 to 4095 plus an approximate
percent value.

Relay / electromagnetic lock output test:

```text
Pico GPIO 18 -> relay module IN
Pico GND     -> relay module GND
Relay VCC    -> relay module supply required by your module
```

This test toggles GPIO 18 every second. Do not connect a real lock until the
relay module toggles correctly with a meter or indicator LED.

Smart film relay output test:

```text
Pico GPIO 15 -> relay/driver IN
Pico GND     -> relay/driver GND
Driver VCC   -> driver supply required by your module
```

This test toggles GPIO 15 every second. Test the relay/driver first before
connecting the actual smart film power circuit.

Raspberry Pi sound and display diagnostics:

Sound and TV/display output are Raspberry Pi controller responsibilities, so
they are not wired to this Pico diagnostic project.

To test the crashing plates file directly on the Raspberry Pi:

```bash
ffplay -nodisp -autoexit /home/admin/escape-room/assets/crashing_plates.m4a
```

To verify the controller-side message path, run the Raspberry Pi controller and
watch the terminal for display output when the room reaches the color-button
stage. The expected message is:

```text
Bake at 350 Degrees
```
